#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:1
msgid "Iterating over More Complex Data with `<For/>`"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:3
msgid ""
"This chapter goes into iteration over nested data structures in a bit more "
"depth. It belongs here with the other chapter on iteration, but feel free to "
"skip it and come back if you’d like to stick with simpler subjects for now."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:8
msgid "The Problem"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:10
msgid ""
"I just said that the framework does not rerender any of the items in one of "
"the rows, unless the key has changed. This probably makes sense at first, "
"but it can easily trip you up."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:14
msgid ""
"Let’s consider an example in which each of the items in our row is some data "
"structure. Imagine, for example, that the items come from some JSON array of "
"keys and values:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:25
msgid ""
"Let’s define a simple component that will iterate over the rows and display "
"each one:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:30 src/view/04b_iteration.md:167
msgid "// start with a set of three rows\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:33 src/view/04b_iteration.md:170
msgid "\"foo\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:37 src/view/04b_iteration.md:174
msgid "\"bar\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:41 src/view/04b_iteration.md:178
msgid "\"baz\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:46 src/view/04b_iteration.md:183
msgid ""
"// when we click, update each row,\n"
"        // doubling its value\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:54 src/view/04b_iteration.md:189
msgid "// log the new value of the signal\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:55 src/view/04b_iteration.md:190
msgid "\"{:?}\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:57 src/view/04b_iteration.md:192
msgid "\"Update Values\""
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:59 src/view/04b_iteration.md:194
msgid "// iterate over the rows and display each value\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:71
msgid ""
"Note the `let(child)` syntax here. In the previous chapter we introduced "
"`<For/>` with a `children` prop. We can actually create this value directly "
"in the children of the `<For/>` component, without breaking out of the "
"`view` macro: the `let(child)` combined with `<p>{child.value}</p>` above is "
"the equivalent of"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:80
msgid ""
"For convenience, you can also choose to destructure the pattern of your data:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:90
msgid ""
"When you click the `Update Values` button... nothing happens. Or rather: the "
"signal is updated, the new value is logged, but the `{child.value}` for each "
"row doesn’t update."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:94
msgid ""
"Let’s see: is that because we forgot to add a closure to make it reactive? "
"Let’s try `{move || child.value}`."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:97
msgid "...Nope. Still nothing."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:99
msgid ""
"Here’s the problem: as I said, each row is only rerendered when the key "
"changes. We’ve updated the value for each row, but not the key for any of "
"the rows, so nothing has rerendered. And if you look at the type of `child."
"value`, it’s a plain `i32`, not a reactive `ReadSignal<i32>` or something. "
"This means that even if we wrap a closure around it, the value in this row "
"will never update."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:105
msgid "We have four possible solutions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:107
msgid ""
"change the `key` so that it always updates when the data structure changes"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:108
msgid "change the `value` so that it’s reactive"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:109
msgid ""
"take a reactive slice of the data structure instead of using each row "
"directly"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:110
msgid "use a `Store`"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:112
msgid "Option 1: Change the Key"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:114
msgid ""
"Each row is only rerendered when the key changes. Our rows above didn’t "
"rerender, because the key didn’t change. So: why not just force the key to "
"change?"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:127
msgid ""
"Now we include both the key and the value in the `key`. This means that "
"whenever the value of a row changes, `<For/>` will treat it as if it’s an "
"entirely new row, and replace the previous one."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:131 src/view/04b_iteration.md:221
#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:294 src/view/04b_iteration.md:370
msgid "Pros"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:133
msgid ""
"This is very easy. We can make it even easier by deriving `PartialEq`, `Eq`, "
"and `Hash` on `DatabaseEntry`, in which case we could just `key=|state| "
"state.clone()`."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:136 src/view/04b_iteration.md:227
#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:299 src/view/04b_iteration.md:376
msgid "Cons"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:138
msgid ""
"**This is the least efficient of the four options.** Every time the value of "
"a row changes, it throws out the previous `<p>` element and replaces it with "
"an entirely new one. Rather than making a fine-grained update to the text "
"node, in other words, it really does rerender the entire row on every "
"change, and this is expensive in proportion to how complex the UI of the row "
"is."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:144
msgid ""
"You’ll notice we also end up cloning the whole data structure so that `<For/"
">` can hold onto a copy of the key. For more complex structures, this can "
"become a bad idea fast!"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:147
msgid "Option 2: Nested Signals"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:149
msgid ""
"If we do want that fine-grained reactivity for the value, one option is to "
"wrap the `value` of each row in a signal."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:160
msgid ""
"`RwSignal<_>` is a “read-write signal,” which combines the getter and setter "
"in one object. I’m using it here because it’s a little easier to store in a "
"struct than separate getters and setters."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:206
msgid ""
"This version works! And if you look in the DOM inspector in your browser, "
"you’ll see that unlike in the previous version, in this version only the "
"individual text nodes are updated. Passing the signal directly into `{child."
"value}` works, as signals do keep their reactivity if you pass them into the "
"view."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:211
msgid ""
"Note that I changed the `set_data.update()` to a `data.read()`. `.read()` is "
"a non-cloning way of accessing a signal’s value. In this case, we are only "
"updating the inner values, not updating the list of values: because signals "
"maintain their own state, we don’t actually need to update the `data` signal "
"at all, so the immutable `.read()` is fine here."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:217
msgid ""
"In fact, this version doesn’t update `data`, so the `<For/>` is essentially "
"a static list as in the last chapter, and this could just be a plain "
"iterator. But the `<For/>` is useful if we want to add or remove rows in the "
"future."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:223
msgid ""
"This is the most efficient option, and fits directly with the rest of the "
"mental model of the framework: values that change over time are wrapped in "
"signals so the interface can respond to them."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:229
msgid ""
"Nested reactivity can be cumbersome if you’re receiving data from an API or "
"another data source you don’t control, and you don’t want to create a "
"different struct wrapping each field in a signal."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:233
msgid "Option 3: Memoized Slices"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:235
msgid ""
"Leptos provides a primitive called a [`Memo`](https://docs.rs/leptos/latest/"
"leptos/reactive/computed/struct.Memo.html), which creates a derived "
"computation that only triggers a reactive update when its value has changed."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:239
msgid ""
"This allows you to create reactive values for subfields of a larger data "
"structure, without needing to wrap the fields of that structure in signals. "
"In combination with [`<ForEnumerate/>`](https://docs.rs/leptos/latest/leptos/"
"control_flow/fn.ForEnumerate.html), this will allow us to rerender only "
"changed data values."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:244
msgid ""
"Most of the application can remain the same as the initial (broken) version, "
"but the `<For/>` will be updated to this:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:262
msgid "You’ll notice a few differences here:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:264
msgid ""
"we use `ForEnumerate` rather than `For`, so we have access to an `index` "
"signal"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:265
msgid ""
"we use the `children` prop explicitly, to make it easier to run some non-"
"`view` code"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:266
msgid ""
"we define a `value` memo and use that in the view. This `value` field "
"doesn’t actually use the `child` being passed into each row. Instead, it "
"uses the index and reaches back into the original `data` to get the value."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:270
msgid ""
"Now every time `data` changes, each memo will be recalculated. If its value "
"has changed, it will update its text node, without rerendering the whole row."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:273
msgid ""
"**Note**: It is not safe to use `For` for this with an enumerated iterator, "
"as in an earlier version of this example:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:290
msgid ""
"In this case, changes to values in `data` will be reacted to, but changes to "
"ordering will not, as the Memo will always use the `index` it was initially "
"created with. This will result in duplicate entries in the rendered output "
"if any items are moved."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:296
msgid ""
"We get the same fine-grained reactivity of the signal-wrapped version, "
"without needing to wrap the data in signals."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:301
msgid ""
"It’s a bit more complex to set up this memo-per-row inside the "
"`<ForEnumerate/>` loop rather than using nested signals. For example, you’ll "
"notice that we have to guard against the possibility that the `data[index."
"get()]` would panic by using `data.get(index.get())`, because this memo may "
"be triggered to re-run once just after the row is removed. (This is because "
"the memo for each row and the whole `<ForEnumerate/>` both depend on the "
"same `data` signal, and the order of execution for multiple reactive values "
"that depend on the same signal isn’t guaranteed.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:308
msgid ""
"Note also that while memos memoize their reactive changes, the same "
"calculation does need to re-run to check the value every time, so nested "
"reactive signals will still be more efficient for pinpoint updates here."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:312
msgid "Option 4: Stores"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:314
msgid ""
"Some of this content is duplicated in the section on global state management "
"with stores [here](../15_global_state.md#option-3-create-a-global-state-"
"store). Both sections are intermediate/optional content, so I thought some "
"duplication couldn’t hurt."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:316
msgid ""
"Leptos 0.7 introduces a new reactive primitive called “stores.” Stores are "
"designed to address the issues described in this chapter so far. They’re a "
"bit experimental, so they require an additional dependency called "
"`reactive_stores` in your `Cargo.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:319
msgid ""
"Stores give you fine-grained reactive access to the individual fields of a "
"struct, and to individual items in collections like `Vec<_>`, without "
"needing to create nested signals or memos manually, as in the options given "
"above."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:321
msgid ""
"Stores are built on top of the `Store` derive macro, which creates a getter "
"for each field of a struct. Calling this getter gives reactive access to "
"that particular field. Reading from it will track only that field and its "
"parents/children, and updating it will only notify that field and its "
"parents/children, but not siblings. In other words, mutating `value` will "
"not notify `key`, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:323
msgid "We can adapt the data types we used in the examples above."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:325
msgid ""
"The top level of a store always needs to be a struct, so we’ll create a "
"`Data` wrapper with a single `rows` field."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:341
msgid ""
"Adding `#[store(key)]` to the `rows` field allows us to have keyed access to "
"the fields of the store, which will be useful in the `<For/>` component "
"below. We can simply use `key`, the same key that we’ll use in `<For/>`."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:343
msgid "The `<For/>` component is pretty straightforward:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:356
msgid ""
"Because `rows` is a keyed field, it implements `IntoIterator`, and we can "
"simply use `move || data.rows()` as the `each` prop. This will react to any "
"changes to the `rows` list, just as `move || data.get()` did in our nested-"
"signal version."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:358
msgid ""
"The `key` field calls `.read()` to get access to the current value of the "
"row, then clones and returns the `key` field."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:360
msgid ""
"In `children` prop, calling `child.value()` gives us reactive access to the "
"`value` field for the row with this key. If rows are reordered, added, or "
"removed, the keyed store field will keep in sync so that this `value` is "
"always associated with the correct key."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:362
msgid ""
"In the update button handler, we’ll iterate over the entries in `rows`, "
"updating each one:"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:372
msgid ""
"We get the fine-grained reactivity of the nested-signal and memo versions, "
"without needing to manually create nested signals or memoized slices. We can "
"work with plain data (a struct and `Vec<_>`), annotated with a derive macro, "
"rather than special nested reactive types."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:374
msgid ""
"Personally, I think the stores version is the nicest one here. And no "
"surprise, as it’s the newest API. We’ve had a few years to think about these "
"things and stores include some of the lessons we’ve learned!"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:378
msgid ""
"On the other hand, it’s the newest API. As of writing this sentence "
"(December 2024), stores have only been released for a few weeks; I am sure "
"that there are still some bugs or edge cases to be figured out."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:380
msgid "Full Example"
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:382
msgid ""
"Here’s the complete store example. You can find another, more complete "
"example [here](https://github.com/leptos-rs/leptos/blob/main/examples/stores/"
"src/lib.rs), and more discussion in the book [here](../15_global_state.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/view/04b_iteration.md:384
msgid ""
"```\n"
"use reactive_stores::Store;\n"
"\n"
"#[derive(Store, Debug, Clone)]\n"
"pub struct Data {\n"
"    #[store(key: String = |row| row.key.clone())]\n"
"    rows: Vec<DatabaseEntry>,\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[derive(Store, Debug, Clone)]\n"
"struct DatabaseEntry {\n"
"    key: String,\n"
"    value: i32,\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[component]\n"
"pub fn App() -> impl IntoView {\n"
"    // instead of a signal with the rows, we create a store for Data\n"
"    let data = Store::new(Data {\n"
"        rows: vec![\n"
"            DatabaseEntry {\n"
"                key: \"foo\".to_string(),\n"
"                value: 10,\n"
"            },\n"
"            DatabaseEntry {\n"
"                key: \"bar\".to_string(),\n"
"                value: 20,\n"
"            },\n"
"            DatabaseEntry {\n"
"                key: \"baz\".to_string(),\n"
"                value: 15,\n"
"            },\n"
"        ],\n"
"    });\n"
"\n"
"    view! {\n"
"        // when we click, update each row,\n"
"        // doubling its value\n"
"        <button on:click=move |_| {\n"
"            // allows iterating over the entries in an iterable store field\n"
"            use reactive_stores::StoreFieldIterator;\n"
"\n"
"            // calling rows() gives us access to the rows\n"
"            for row in data.rows().iter_unkeyed() {\n"
"                *row.value().write() *= 2;\n"
"            }\n"
"            // log the new value of the signal\n"
"            leptos::logging::log!(\"{:?}\", data.get());\n"
"        }>\n"
"            \"Update Values\"\n"
"        </button>\n"
"        // iterate over the rows and display each value\n"
"        <For\n"
"            each=move || data.rows()\n"
"            key=|row| row.read().key.clone()\n"
"            children=|child| {\n"
"                let value = child.value();\n"
"                view! { <p>{move || value.get()}</p> }\n"
"            }\n"
"        />\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"```"
msgstr ""
